{"cursor":"28036","size":15,"audio":[],"currentlang":"en","article":"\n\n'Neuropsychology' studies the structure and function of the brain as they relate\nto specific psychological processes and behaviors. It is seen as a clinical and\nexperimental field of psychology that aims to study, assess, understand and\ntreat behaviors directly related to brain functioning. The term neuropsychology\nhas been applied to lesion studies in humans and animals. It has also been\napplied to efforts to record electrical activity from individual cells (or\ngroups of cells) in higher primates (including some studies of human\npatients). Posner, M. I. & DiGirolamo, G. J. (2000)\nCognitive Neuroscience:Origins and Promise,Psychological Bulletin, 126:6, 873-\n889. It is scientific in its approach, making use of neuroscience, and\nshares an information processing view of the mind with cognitive psychology and\ncognitive science.\n\nIn practice neuropsychologists tend to work in clinical settings (involved in\nassessing or treating patients with neuropsychological problemssee clinical\nneuropsychology), forensic settings or industry (often as consultants where\nneuropsychological knowledge is applied to product design or in the management\nof pharmaceutical clinical-trials research for drugs that might have a potential\nimpact on CNS functioning).\n","linknr":636,"url":"Neuropsychology","recorded":1362373671,"links":76,"instances":["neuropsychology"],"pdf":[],"categories":["Neuropsychology|","Clinical psychology","Branches of psychology"],"headings":["History","Approaches","Methods and tools","See also","References"],"image":["//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/b/ba/Thomas_Willis.jpg/110px-Thomas_Willis.jpg","//bits.wikimedia.org/static-1.21wmf10/skins/common/images/magnify-clip.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/8/89/Jean-Baptiste_Bouillaud.jpg/150px-Jean-Baptiste_Bouillaud.jpg","//bits.wikimedia.org/static-1.21wmf10/skins/common/images/magnify-clip.png","//